<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="365" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1124,1760]" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,1124,1149]" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bates, H. W." box="[275,479,1124,1149]" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" pagination="144 - 164" refId="ref4807" refString="Bates, H. W. (1864) Contributions to an Insect Fauna of the Amazon Valley. Coleoptera: Longicornes, (Part XIX). The Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 3 (13), 144 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222936408681590" type="journal article" year="1864">Bates (1864: 151)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[603,858,1124,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Nyssodrys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinerascens">
<emphasis box="[603,858,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Nyssodrys cinerascens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(currently 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[985,1276,1124,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Nyssodrysina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinerascens">
<emphasis box="[985,1276,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Nyssodrysina cinerascens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) based on six specimens of both sexes. According to the author, it would be common in 
<collectingRegion box="[1012,1065,1160,1184]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Pará</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1078,1150,1159,1184]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. Currently, the species is widely distributed in northern South America, in Amazonian regions. On the next page of the same work, Bates (1964: 152) described (in note) 
<taxonomicName box="[532,751,1232,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Nyssodrys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lignaria">
<emphasis box="[532,751,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Nyssodrys lignaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(currently 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bates, 1864))" authorityName="" authorityYear="1864" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[885,1319,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Nyssodrysina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lignaria">
<emphasis box="[885,1138,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Nyssodrysina lignaria</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bates, H. W." box="[1150,1319,1231,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" pagination="144 - 164" refId="ref4807" refString="Bates, H. W. (1864) Contributions to an Insect Fauna of the Amazon Valley. Coleoptera: Longicornes, (Part XIX). The Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 3 (13), 144 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222936408681590" type="journal article" year="1864">(Bates, 1864))</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. This last species was described based on a couple specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[809,977,1268,1293]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[989,1061,1268,1293]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. Currently, this species occurs in the eastern littoral of 
<collectingCountry box="[395,463,1303,1328]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Atlantic Forest), in 
<collectingCountry box="[703,807,1304,1328]" name="Paraguay" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[864,979,1303,1328]" name="Argentina" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. Although the two species have disjunct distribution, they are extremely similar. Neither Bates (1984) nor other authors made any comparison between them, and in order to aid future identifications, we examined both species and we noticed some differences that we think are useful for separating them.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1124,1760]" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[199,489,1448,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Nyssodrysina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinerascens">
<emphasis box="[199,489,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">Nyssodrysina cinerascens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[640,764,1448,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Nyssodrysina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lignaria">
<emphasis box="[640,764,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">N. lignaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the posterior margin of the pronotum without punctures or with these sparsely distributed; by the elytra without longitudinal carinae and by scutellum sparsely pubescent. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[180,303,1520,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Nyssodrysina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lignaria">
<emphasis box="[180,303,1520,1544]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="365">N. lignaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the posterior margin of pronotum has a row of punctures (closely distributed); the elytra have carinae (or longitudinal elevations) and the scutellum presents a central area of contrasting whitish pubescence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
